---
import Layout from '../components/Layout.astro';

const modules = [
  { name: 'DNS', text: 'A/AAAA, NS, MX, TXT/SPF, DMARC, DKIM hints, DNSSEC posture, DoH-backed.' },
  { name: 'HTTP', text: 'Redirect chain, status, headers, HSTS, CSP, cookies, caching, inline body decoders.' },
  { name: 'TLS', text: 'Certificate Transparency logs + live peer handshake (via headless browser fallback) where supported.' },
  { name: 'Email posture', text: 'SPF alignment, DMARC policy strength, MX hygiene, DKIM presence hints.' },
  { name: 'CDN / infra', text: 'ASN, anycast detection, front-door inference, PTR clustering, Shodan-facet exposure.' },
  { name: 'Findings & fixes', text: 'Correlation across modules, likely root causes, and reproducible shell commands you can paste.' },
];

const acknowledgments = [
  { who: 'SSLMate Certspotter + crt.sh', for: 'Certificate Transparency logs' },
  { who: 'Team Cymru', for: 'ASN / IP-to-network mapping' },
  { who: 'ipwho.is', for: 'geolocation and ISP hints' },
  { who: 'Shodan free facets', for: 'port / product / CVE exposure summaries' },
  { who: 'Cloudflare', for: 'Pages, Functions, Browser Rendering' },
];
---

<Layout title="About netrecon - correlated network diagnostics">
  <section class="about-hero">
    <div class="prompt mono">
      <span class="p-host">netrecon</span>:<span class="p-path">~/about</span>$ <span class="typed">cat README.md</span>
    </div>

    <h1 class="about-h1">netrecon</h1>
    <p class="about-lede">
      Correlated network diagnostics for engineers. One input - domain, IP, or URL -
      runs DNS, HTTP, TLS, email posture, and CDN / infra checks, correlates the
      findings, and gives you likely root causes plus reproducible commands to
      verify yourself.
    </p>
    <div class="about-pills mono">
      <span class="pill">edge-only</span>
      <span class="pill">stateless</span>
      <span class="pill">no account</span>
      <span class="pill">MCP-ready</span>
      <span class="pill">JSON out</span>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="about-section">
    <h2 class="about-h2">Why this, not another DNS checker</h2>
    <p class="about-muted">
      Most tools give you a wall of raw data and leave the reasoning to you. netrecon is
      opinionated: it runs multiple checks, correlates them, and tells you which finding
      matters. You still get the raw data, the JSON, and the exact shell commands to
      reproduce the result on your own machine - but the first thing you see is
      <em>what's probably wrong</em>.
    </p>
    <p class="about-muted">
      Built for SREs who land on an unfamiliar site mid-incident and need a one-page
      read of its posture, and for engineers who want DNS / HTTP / TLS / CDN / email
      answered in one pass instead of bouncing between six tabs.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="about-section">
    <h2 class="about-h2">What it checks</h2>
    <ul class="module-list">
      {modules.map((m) => (
        <li class="module">
          <span class="module-k mono">{m.name}</span>
          <span class="module-v">{m.text}</span>
        </li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="about-section">
    <h2 class="about-h2">How it works</h2>
    <p class="about-muted">
      Astro-built static frontend on Cloudflare Pages. Every check runs in Cloudflare
      Pages Functions at the edge. No servers, no queues, no database. Requests are
      stateless - nothing about your input is stored.
    </p>
    <p class="about-muted">
      Rate-limited in-code via the Cache API at the Worker layer - no external
      dependency. Input validation and SSRF guards live in a shared tool registry so
      the HTTP API, the web UI, and the MCP server all enforce the same rules.
    </p>
    <p class="about-muted">
      Agents can call netrecon as an MCP server - see
      <a href="/mcp">the MCP page</a> for Claude Desktop, Cursor, and VS Code configs.
      Programmatic clients can hit <code class="mono">/api/analyze</code>,
      <code class="mono">/api/compare</code>, <code class="mono">/api/whoami</code>,
      and <code class="mono">/api/health</code> directly.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="about-section">
    <h2 class="about-h2">Trust posture</h2>
    <ul class="trust-list">
      <li><strong>No accounts, no email gating.</strong> The site is public and anonymous.</li>
      <li><strong>No input logging.</strong> What you analyze is not persisted. The edge runtime is stateless by design.</li>
      <li><strong>No ads, no trackers.</strong> Zero third-party JS.</li>
      <li><strong>Rate-limited.</strong> 10/min for <code class="mono">/api/analyze</code> and <code class="mono">/api/compare</code>, 20/min for <code class="mono">/api/mcp</code>, 60/min for <code class="mono">/api/whoami</code>. Per-IP.</li>
      <li><strong>SSRF-guarded.</strong> Inputs that resolve to private / loopback / link-local ranges are rejected at the tool boundary.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="about-section">
    <h2 class="about-h2">Known limitations</h2>
    <p class="about-muted">
      We try to be honest about what the edge can and can't do from inside a Worker.
    </p>
    <ul class="trust-list">
      <li>
        <strong>TLS chain from CT logs is not a live handshake.</strong> For most targets
        we fall back to Certificate Transparency logs (Certspotter / crt.sh). The chain
        you see is what <em>was issued</em>, not what the peer <em>is currently serving</em>.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Browser Rendering path loses issuer.</strong> When netrecon uses
        Cloudflare Browser Rendering to capture a real TLS 1.3 handshake, Chrome's
        security state doesn't expose the certificate issuer. This is a browser
        limitation, not ours. See <a href="/blog/" >the blog</a> for the full write-up.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>No IPv6-only clients.</strong> Outbound fetches use whatever the Worker
        runtime picks - typically v4 where available.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Not an uptime monitor.</strong> We give you a point-in-time snapshot.
        We don't poll, alert, or track history.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="about-section">
    <h2 class="about-h2">Acknowledgments</h2>
    <p class="about-muted">
      netrecon is a frontend for a lot of other people's excellent work.
    </p>
    <ul class="ack-list">
      {acknowledgments.map((a) => (
        <li class="ack">
          <span class="ack-who mono">{a.who}</span>
          <span class="ack-for">{a.for}</span>
        </li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="about-section">
    <h2 class="about-h2">Credits</h2>
    <p>
      Built by Yossi Ben Hagai -
      <a href="https://yossibh.github.io/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">yossibh.github.io</a>.
    </p>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .about-hero { padding: 32px 0 8px; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); margin-bottom: 28px; }
  .about-hero .prompt { font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 13px; color: var(--fg-dim); margin: 0 0 18px; }
  .about-hero .prompt .p-host { color: var(--accent); }
  .about-hero .prompt .p-path { color: var(--low); }
  .about-hero .prompt .typed { color: var(--fg); }
  .about-h1 { font-size: 38px; line-height: 1.1; margin: 0 0 12px; letter-spacing: -0.015em; }
  .about-lede { font-size: 17px; color: var(--fg-dim); max-width: 760px; margin: 0 0 18px; }
  .about-lede em { color: var(--fg); font-style: italic; }
  .about-pills { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 6px; margin: 0; }
  .about-pills .pill {
    font-size: 11px; color: var(--fg-dim); border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 999px; padding: 3px 10px; background: var(--bg-elev);
  }

  .about-section { padding: 28px 0; border-bottom: 1px dashed var(--border); }
  .about-section:last-of-type { border-bottom: 0; }
  .about-h2 {
    font-size: 12px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.16em;
    color: var(--accent); font-family: var(--mono); margin: 0 0 14px; font-weight: 600;
  }
  .about-h2::before { content: "# "; color: var(--fg-dim); }
  .about-muted { color: var(--fg-dim); max-width: 760px; margin-top: 0; }
  .about-muted em { color: var(--fg); font-style: italic; }

  .module-list { list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 10px 0 0; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 6px; }
  .module { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 140px 1fr; gap: 14px; align-items: baseline; padding: 4px 0; border-left: 2px solid var(--accent-dim); padding-left: 12px; }
  .module-k { color: var(--accent); font-size: 11px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.12em; }
  .module-v { color: var(--fg); }

  .trust-list { list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 10px 0 0; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 8px; max-width: 780px; }
  .trust-list li { padding-left: 16px; position: relative; color: var(--fg-dim); }
  .trust-list li::before { content: "›"; position: absolute; left: 0; color: var(--accent); }
  .trust-list strong { color: var(--fg); font-weight: 600; }
  .trust-list code { background: var(--bg-elev); padding: 1px 6px; border-radius: 3px; font-size: 12px; border: 1px solid var(--border); }

  .ack-list { list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 10px 0 0; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 6px; }
  .ack { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 240px 1fr; gap: 14px; align-items: baseline; padding: 4px 0; }
  .ack-who { color: var(--fg); font-size: 13px; }
  .ack-for { color: var(--fg-dim); font-size: 13px; }

  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .about-h1 { font-size: 28px; }
    .about-lede { font-size: 15px; }
    .module, .ack { grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 2px; }
  }
</style>
